<subSubSection pageId="85" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="85.[142,671,924,1768]" pageId="85">
ETYMOLOGY: The species is named 
<taxonomicName authorityName="BOSSELAERS &amp; JOCQUÉ" authorityYear="2000" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Hortipes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="centralis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="85">centralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because it was collected in the central part of 
<collectingCountry box="[228,308,1129,1152]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="85">Congo</collectingCountry>
, the so­called 
<emphasis box="[478,663,1129,1152]" italics="true" pageId="85">cuvette centrale</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="85" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="85.[142,671,924,1768]" pageId="85">DIAGNOSIS: Females are easily recognized by the simple epigyne combined with very complex, heavily looped IDs almost completely hiding the ST from view.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="85" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="85.[142,671,924,1768]" box="[171,378,1276,1299]" pageId="85">MALE: Unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="85.[142,671,924,1768]" pageId="85">
FEMALE: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[293,495,1305,1329]" pageId="85">Measurements.</emphasis>
Total length 2.59; carapace 1.13 long, 0.92 wide; length of fe: I 0.95, II?, III 0.78, IV 1.13. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="85">Leg spination.</emphasis>
Fe: I rv 2–3; IV plt 0 rlt 1; ti: I, II vsp 6; mt: III plt 1 vt 0 rlt 0; IV plt 1 vt 2 rlt 1. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[240,381,1451,1475]" pageId="85">Coloration.</emphasis>
Carapace and legs yellow, chelicerae and sternum pale yellow. Abdomen peach, without pattern, rather densely covered with thin, pointed grey setae. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="85">Genitalia.</emphasis>
Epigyne restricted to two hemicircular ID entrances, situated anterior to ST and close to symmetry axis (fig. 27c). Vulva: first stretch of ID wide, thick walled, and associated with gland, connected to ST1 through complex sequence of horseshoe loops and coils, 2 Χ passing along dorsal side of ST1
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
